===Intransitive verb===
{{en-infl-reg-consonant|walk||}}

#To [[move]] on the [[feet]] by [[alternately]] [[setting]] each [[foot]] (or pairs of feet, in the case of [[quadruped]]s) [[forward]], with at least one foot on the [[ground]] at all times.  Compare '''[[run]]'''.
# {{colloquial}} {{law}} To go [[free]], particularly when [[actually]] [[guilty]].
#:''If you can’t present a better case, that robber is going to walk.''
# {{colloquial}} Of an object, to be [[stolen]].
#:''If you leave your wallet lying around, it’s going to walk.''
#{{cricket}} (''of a batsman'') To walk off the field, as if [[given]] [[out]], after the [[fielding]] [[side]] [[appeal]]s and before the [[umpire]] has [[ruled]]; done as a matter of [[sportsmanship]] when the batsman knows he is out.

====Synonyms====
*(''move upon two feet''): [[ambulate]] (''technical'')
*(''colloquial: go free''): be [[acquit]]ted, [[get off]], [[go free]]
*(''be stolen''): be/get [[steal|stolen]]; {{UK}} be/get [[nick]]ed, be/get [[pinch]]ed

